# JWT Authentication Implementation Plan

## Context

The Express API (`src/`) already has full CRUD for posts and comments but has **zero authentication**. The test suite (`tests/auth.test.ts`) is already written and expects:
- `POST /auth/register` and `POST /auth/login` endpoints
- Bearer JWT tokens (secret: `"super-secret-key"`) in `Authorization` header
- POST/PUT/DELETE routes protected (401 without token)
- Ownership enforcement on PUT/DELETE (403 for non-owners)
- GET routes remain public

No new dependencies are needed — `jsonwebtoken` and `@types/jsonwebtoken` are already in `package.json`.

---

## Files to Create

### 1. `src/middleware/auth.ts` — JWT verify middleware

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

export function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Authentication required" });
    return;
  }
  const token = authHeader.split(" ")[1];
  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { userId: number; username: string };
    req.user = payload;
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/routes/auth.ts` — Register & Login endpoints

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";

const router = Router();
const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;
  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }
  if (users.find((u) => u.username === username)) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }
  const newUser = { id: nextId(users), username, email, password };
  users.push(newUser);
  const token = jwt.sign({ userId: newUser.id, username: newUser.username }, JWT_SECRET);
  const { password: _, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser;
  res.status(201).json({ token, user: userWithoutPassword });
});

// POST /auth/login
router.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;
  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== password) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }
  const token = jwt.sign({ userId: user.id, username: user.username }, JWT_SECRET);
  res.json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

**Notes:**
- Passwords stored/compared as plaintext (no `bcrypt` in deps; tests don't require hashing)
- `userId` in JWT payload matches what posts routes will attach to `req.user`
- Registration returns `{ token, user }` — `user` omits password (destructuring)
- Login returns `{ token }` only (tests don't check for `user` on login)
- Duplicate username → 409; missing fields → 400

---

## Files to Modify

### 3. `src/types.ts` — Extend Express `Request` with `user`

Add at the bottom of the existing file (after the existing interfaces):

```typescript
export interface AuthPayload {
  userId: number;
  username: string;
}

declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: AuthPayload;
    }
  }
}
```

This uses module augmentation (valid inside a module with existing `export` statements) to give TypeScript knowledge of `req.user` across all route files.

### 4. `src/routes/posts.ts` — Apply auth middleware + ownership checks

Changes:
- Import `authenticate` from `../middleware/auth.js`
- **POST `/`**: Add `authenticate` middleware; derive `userId` from `req.user!.userId` (ignore body's `userId`)
- **PUT `/:id`**: Add `authenticate` middleware; after finding post, check `req.user!.userId === post.userId` → 403 if not
- **DELETE `/:id`**: Same ownership check as PUT

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts — public
router.get("/", (req, res) => { res.json(posts); });

// GET /posts/:id — public
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === id);
  if (!post) { res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" }); return; }
  res.json(post);
});

// POST /posts — requires auth; userId from token
router.post("/", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.userId,   // ← from token, not body
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id — requires auth + ownership
router.put("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) { res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" }); return; }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" }); return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id — requires auth + ownership
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) { res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" }); return; }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" }); return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as postsRouter };
```

### 5. `src/routes/comments.ts` — Apply auth middleware + ownership checks

Same pattern as posts:
- **GET** routes: unchanged (public)
- **POST `/posts/:postId/comments`**: Add `authenticate`; use `req.user!.userId` instead of body's `userId`
- **PUT `/comments/:id`**: Add `authenticate`; check ownership → 403 if not owner
- **DELETE `/comments/:id`**: Add `authenticate`; check ownership → 403 if not owner

### 6. `src/app.ts` — Mount auth router

```typescript
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";
// ...existing imports...

app.use("/auth", authRouter);   // add this line
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);
```

---

## Execution Order

1. Add `AuthPayload` + `declare global` augmentation to `src/types.ts`
2. Create `src/middleware/auth.ts`
3. Create `src/routes/auth.ts`
4. Update `src/routes/posts.ts` (add import + middleware + ownership checks)
5. Update `src/routes/comments.ts` (same pattern)
6. Update `src/app.ts` (mount `/auth` router)

---

## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| Plaintext passwords | No `bcrypt` in deps; tests register then immediately login with same string |
| JWT payload: `{ userId, username }` | `userId` must be a number (test checks `typeof res.body.userId === "number"`) |
| `authenticate` as inline route middleware | Cleaner than global middleware; keeps GET routes public without extra logic |
| Module augmentation in `types.ts` | Cleanest location; file is already a module (has `export`) |
| `req.user!.userId` (non-null assertion) | Safe because `authenticate` always sets it before handlers run |

---

